{
  "doc_id": "39571",
  "text": "There is also a group of MT-severing proteins that regulate synaptic MT stability and growth at the NMJ. These are Spastin [CITATION_1] and Katanin 60 (Mao et al., 2014) . Spastin is enriched in axons and is highly abundant in presynaptic terminals. Knockdown of Spastin causes a severe reduction in synaptic arbor and an increase in stable and looped MTs at synaptic terminals [CITATION_2] . Similarly, loss of Katanin 60 also resulted in increased MT loops and levels of Ac-Tub (Mao et al., 2014) suggesting that these protein functions are contrasting to that of Ringer and Futsch. Vertebrate Spastin is critically required for axonal outgrowth during zebrafish embryonic development [CITATION_3] . Also, axon branch loss at the developing mouse NMJ is mediated by branch-specific MT severing by Spastin, which results in local disassembly of the MT cytoskeleton with subsequent dismantling of branches [CITATION_4] . Mutations in Spastin have also been associated with increased stabilization of MT network [CITATION_5] . Recently, it has also been shown that in HeLa cells, the two isoforms of Spastin harboring a missense mutation increases the levels of Ac-Tub [CITATION_6] . Thus, the broader implications from all of these findings could be that a fine balance of acetylation/de-acetylation kinetics may underlie proper MT organization and synaptogenesis.",
